proposals.codeSnippet:
using System.IO.Compression;

// .lottie files are ZIP archives containing Lottie JSON
using var archive = ZipFile.OpenRead("path/to/animation.lottie");
var jsonEntry = archive.Entries.FirstOrDefault(e =>
    e.FullName.EndsWith(".json", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase) &&
    !e.FullName.Equals("manifest.json", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase));

if (jsonEntry != null)
{
    using var stream = jsonEntry.Open();
    using var ms = new MemoryStream();
    stream.CopyTo(ms);
    ms.Position = 0;
    var animation = SkiaSharp.Skottie.Animation.Create(ms);
    if (animation != null)
    {
        // Use the animation
    }
}

actions.comment:
Thanks for the report. The issue here is that `.lottie` files use the **dotLottie format**, which is a ZIP archive containing Lottie JSON — it's not raw JSON itself. Skottie (both in Skia and SkiaSharp) only parses raw Lottie JSON, so passing a ZIP file returns null as expected.

Here's a workaround to extract the JSON from the `.lottie` ZIP:

```csharp
using System.IO.Compression;

using var archive = ZipFile.OpenRead(sourceFileAbsolute);
var jsonEntry = archive.Entries.FirstOrDefault(e =>
    e.FullName.EndsWith(".json", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase) &&
    !e.FullName.Equals("manifest.json", StringComparison.OrdinalIgnoreCase));

if (jsonEntry != null)
{
    using var stream = jsonEntry.Open();
    using var ms = new MemoryStream();
    stream.CopyTo(ms);
    ms.Position = 0;
    var animation = SkiaSharp.Skottie.Animation.Create(ms);
}
```

Alternatively, LottieFiles allows downloading the raw `.json` format directly, which works with `Animation.Create()` without any extraction.
